  "texts": [
    "RMSE offers a more intuitive grasp of the error magnitude compared to the MSE, as it aligns the error metric more closely with the scale of the actual data (Cai et al. 2022).",
    "Mean Absolute Error (MAE) measures the average magnitude of errors between predicted and actual values, ignoring their direction.",
    "It is generally more resilient to outliers compared to MSE, as it does not square the errors, which can disproportionately increase the impact of large outliers (Wang et al. 2022).",
    "Mean Relative Absolute Error (MRAE) is a metric for assessing the average absolute discrepancies between actual and forecasted values, expressed as a proportion of the actual values (Cai et al. 2022).",
    "Back propagation mean absolute error (BPMRAE) is used to calculate the colorimetric accuracy (Zhao et al. 2020b)."
  ],
